TikTok hides undesirable videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under 18 years of age.
Imagine China / Reuters
The Chinese social network TikTok censor videos that mention Tiananmen Square, the independence of Tibet or the banned religious group Falun Gong, tells The Guardian.
The documents that were at the publication say that the owner of TikTok (the company ByteDance) with the help of the application promotes the goals of China's foreign policy abroad.
Most of the violations regarding China's policy fall under "incitement to hatred."
In each case, TikTok places undesirable publications in a context suitable for general rules so that the actions of the social network do not seem censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of China's socialist system falls under the general ban "criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as the constitutional monarchy, the parliamentary system, etc. ."
The ban on the mention of incidents in Tiananmen Square or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the "distortion of the history of China or other countries."
The document also lists the banned names of twenty "foreign leaders or statesmen," including North Korean leaders Kim Jong-il, Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, American presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Kyn Hee, Indonesian President Joko Viddo and Indian Prime Minister Nadra.
The prohibited material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Publications from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may entail blocking the user.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer applied: "Now we use a localized approach for moderation, as well as involve independent local specialists."
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publications, says the co-founder of the "Producer Center" Rustem Bogdanov.
"Producer Center" is one Russian media company that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Producer Center" is coordinated with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be placed without approval, Bogdanov reports.
Asked whether it is possible to speak about politics or Putin in TikTok, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he saw such publications.
The founder of the agency Our Didgit Roman Zaripov agrees with Bogdanov: "The basic rules for users of TikTok list in the user agreement: you can not put shocking content that discriminate against statements and so on."
But under these rules you can bring any content that moderators do not like, says Zaripov.
Zaripov Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
Under the user agreement, only persons over the age of 13 can use TikTok.
The administrators of the social network check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes the faces and determines how many years a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019. ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of the coworking WeWork.
